    "body": "This is indeed very curious. You could capture the traffic to that port, by doing `sudo tcpdump -p tcp -i lo -A  'port 8545'`. It dumps out the `tcp` packets on the `lo` (localhost) network interface, showing the `-A` (ascii) data sent over the wire, for port `8545`.\r\n\r\nThat might show you what is trying to connect to the service. \r\n\r\nAlternatively, you could try (without having the `geth` process running), to start a listener on `8545` which just dumps out the requests: \r\n```\r\n$ ncat -l 8545\r\n```\r\nIf I try to do a `geth attach http://localhost:8545`, this is what pops up: \r\n```\r\nPOST / HTTP/1.1\r\nHost: 127.0.0.1:8545\r\nUser-Agent: Go-http-client/1.1\r\nContent-Length: 47\r\nAccept: application/json\r\nContent-Type: application/json\r\nAccept-Encoding: gzip\r\n\r\n{\"jsonrpc\":\"2.0\",\"id\":1,\"method\":\"rpc_modules\"}\r\n```",
